column28: B, F, and BRPs are presented  in the NEFSC GARM-III report (CRD 08-15).  They indicate the stock is overfished and overfishing occuring.  However, the GARM-III reviewers were somewhat ambiguous about whether to accept this assessment.  They stated that "the proposed analysis could not be used to provide management advice nor stock projections".  However, they went on to state that "there is a substantial probability that it [the stock] is below 1/2 Bmsy".  The NEFMC then developed Multispecies FMP Amendment 16 and based on the GARM-III concluded the stock status was unknown.

column28:
N. red hake:  F Year is filled in with "2009". In reality, the F estimate that is entered in SIS is the average of the estimates from 3 recent years (2007 - 2009).  B Year is filled in with "2010". In reality, the B estimate that is entered in SIS is  the average of the estimates from 3 recent years (2008 - 2010). SIS requires YYYY format and can not accept a range of years.
Basis for F limit and Fmsy needs a new option like “AIM analysis”.
Basis for the B limit should be the average of past survey indices, respectively.  This not currently on the list of options.

Basis for F limit and Fmsy needs a new option like “AIM analysis”.
Basis for the B limit should be the average of past survey indices, respectively.  This not currently on the list of options.

column28:
On July 13, 2012, two changes were made to the 2012.3 halibut record. Funit was changed from “Relative F” to “Instantaneous annual F averaged across ages”.   Fbasis was changed from “U(exploitation rate = C/B)” to “average F (F average across range of ages)”.   The Atlantic halibut assessment uses a surplus production model, called a replacement yield model. Estimated F time series and the Fmsy estimate are both instantaneous rates and are directly comparable. 
 
July 16, 2012 edits: 1. Assessment model changed from:  "Replacement Yield & NFT YPR" to "Surplus Production Model". 2. Bmsy basis changed from: "Surplus Production Model" to "direct estimate".  3. Addition to comment: "Yield per recruit analysis was used to calculate F0.1 as a proxy for Fmsy, then included in the production model by setting r=2*F0.1"

denotes the original estimate of F or SSB. Thus, F2010 = 0.29 becomes 0.36 (=0.29/(1-0.19) and SSB2010 = 2,822 mt becomes 1,680 mt (=2822/(1+0.68). The 2010 estimates of F and SSB were relatively precise (Table D31), with the rho adjusted F remaining within the confidence interval
while the rho adjusted SSB is outside the confidence interval. The Review Panel recommended
use of the rho adjusted F and SSB values for status determination.

column4: Yellowtail flounder - Georges Bank
column28:
In record 2012.7 for GB YT flounder, the estimates that are entered for SSB and F in 2012 were adjusted for the retrospective pattern in the model.  Reporting these values is consistent with the TRAC Status Report 2013/01 which says "a retrospective adjustment ... was applied to the terminal year estimates for both status determination and provision of catch advice".  This is different from what was done last year in the SIS record because it has the unadjusted values entered in SIS.; The point estimates of F and SSB for 2011 that are entered on the SIS form were not adjusted for the retrospective pattern.  If they had been adjusted, the report states that F is expected to increase substantially and 2011 SSB is expected to decrease substantially.

Also, overfishing is now occuring.  This represents a change in stock status from the previous update.

column4: Yellowtail flounder - Southern New England / Mid-Atlantic
column25: NEFSC CRD 12-14 (SAW/SARC 54); NEFMC SSC memo to Paul Howard 24 Sept, 2012; NEFSC Directorate email to NERO (Darcy) Sept. 19, 2012.
column28:
BRP’s were computed using F40%, a proxy for FMSY, and a corresponding SSBMSY proxy derived by sampling age-1 recruitment from an empirical CDF with two alternative recruitment scenarios.  One scenario is based only on age-1 recruitment from a “recent” time period, 1990-2010, recognizing a potential reduction in stock productivity since about 1990. The other scenario uses the entire age-1 recruitment time series from 1973-2010, with “two stanzas” of recruitment determined by whether SSB is either above or below 4,319 mt. 

For both scenarios F40% = 0.316, and overfishing is not occurring.  Stochastic projections at F40% were used to determine biomass reference point proxies (i.e., for SSBMSY and MSY). Conclusions about whether the stock is overfished depend on which recruitment scenario is used, and the SARC could not rule out either scenario.  Therefore, overfished status could not be determined. Under the “recent” recruitment scenario, proxies for SSBMSY = 2,995 mt and MSY = 773 mt, which would lead to the conclusion that the stock is not overfished. Because this stock is under a rebuilding plan with a rebuilding date set for 2014, the stock would also be considered rebuilt.  Under the “two stanza” recruitment scenario, SSBMSY = 22,615 mt and MSY = 5,834 mt, which would lead to the conclusion that the stock is still overfished.

column4: Yellowtail flounder - Georges Bank
column28: Due to a number of modeling problems, the 2014 TRAC agreed to no longer use a VPA assessment model to evaluate GB YT flounder stock status.  An empirical approach has been adopted. The lack of a model framework means that historical estimates of fishing mortality rate, biomass, and recruitment cannot be calculated for this stock. Status determination relative to reference points is not possible because reference points cannot be defined. Some survey biomass estimates are provided, but the report does not explicitly state whether any of the estimates, or a function of the estimates, has been accepted and should be used. Although stock status is now considered unknown (for reasons stated above), the TRAC report has several qualitative statements that strongly suggest stock biomass is low and stock productivity is poor.  These qualitative conclusions about the stock, which are based on trends in resource surveys and fishery catches,  are consistent with descriptions of GB YT flounder stock status contained in previous GB YT stock assessments.  In summary, although stock status is now "unknown" due to the absence of Status Determination Criteria, the authors of the TRAC report concluded that the stock is in poor shape.

column4: Bluefish - Atlantic Coast
column28: In June 2015, SARC-60 retained F40% as a basis for bluefish Biological Reference Points (BRPs), and updated the BRP values with new information.  The Mid-Atlantic Fishery Management Council’s Scientific and Statistical Committee (MAFMC SSC) met in July 2015, shortly after the June 2015 SARC-60 peer review. The SSC made a bluefish ABC recommendation to the MAFMC and based on F35%.  The BRPs associated with F35%, printed in the 27 July 2015 SSC report are: F35% = 0.19, SSBMSY proxy target = 101,343 mt, SSBMSY proxy overfished threshold = 50,672 mt,  MSY proxy = 14,443 mt.  Based on these values, the ratio of SSB to SSB proxy target = 0.85, and the ratio of F2014 to F35% = 0.83.; Bluefish, SAW/SARC60 – in 2015.  Comment 1. Compared to the previous assessment, the ratio of B/Bmsy dropped from .84 (NEAR Bmsy) to .77 (BELOW Bmsy).  Comment 2.  BRPs from the previous assessment were MSY based.  SAW/SARC60 decided to change and recommends using F40% and B40%MSP, due to lack of a clear stock-recruitment relationship.  Comment 3.  The status determination in previous assessments was based on Total Biomass.  SAW/SARC60 decided to change and recommends using Spawning Stock Biomass given the more direct biological link between SSB and recruitment.

column25: Northeast Fisheries Science Center. 2015. Operational Assessment of 20 Northeast Groundfish Stocks, Updated Through 2014. US Dept Commer, Northeast Fish Sci Cent Ref Doc. 15-24; 251 p.
column28:
Cod, GB. 2015. 

a. The 2015 Panel reviewed a revised 2015 assessment. Comments written by the 2015 Panel are specific to the work they reviewed. The 2015 Panel did not re-review the assessment that was reviewed by SAW55, and they did not reject SAW55.

b. The 2015 Panel recommended keeping the SAW55 peer reviewed overfishing defs (i.e., BRPs). 

c. Because the 2015 Panel rejected the revised 2015 version of the assessment model, there are no new and accepted quantitative estimates of SSB, F, or the BRPs.   Nevertheless, the 2015 reviewers felt confident enough to say that the stock is still overfished because SSB was very low based on SAW55, and because none of the information they examined in 2015 indicated that the stock had improved.

d. Overfishing status is less clear.  The 2015 Panel wrote that overfishing status is currently unknown.  They were justified in saying that because there was no way for them to know if the small catch in recent years was large enough to represent overfishing. So, unlike the situation for determining overfished status, the 2015 Panel didn't have enough qualitative or quantitative information to determine whether overfishing was occurring currently.  This leaves the Agency with two possible interpretations:  If the Agency adopts the 2015 Panel conclusion, then overfishing status should be changed to unknown.  If the Agency decides to stick with the older SAW/SARC55 outcome, then overfishing is occurring.

column28:
Cod, GB. 2017  assessment.    
a. The 2017 Panel reviewed an updated “empirical” approach that had been adopted in 2015.    
b.Comments written by the 2017 Panel are specific to the work they reviewed. The 2017 Panel did not re-review previous peer reviewed assessments.    
c. There are no new and accepted quantitative estimates of BRPs. Nevertheless, the 2017 reviewers felt confident enough to say that the stock is still overfished.    
d. Overfishing status is less clear. The 2017operational assessment report lists overfishing status as unknown, but also acknowledges that based on NOAA’s policy, the Agency decided after the 2015 assessment that the stock status would remain as overfishing occurring and overfished based on an earlier benchmark assessment (SAW/SARC55).
e.  The 2017 report includes the averagecatch per tow of 2 recent surveys (7.237 kg/tow) and a relative exploiation rate (0.174), but these are not official status determination criteria.

column28:
Cod, GOM. 2017 assessment. Two models were put forward by SARC55 in 2012. Both models were included in the 2014 assessment update, in the 2015 Operational Assessment, and in this 2017 Operational Assessment. Here are the most recent results from 2017 from both models. Biomass is in mt. F is full F, not retrospective adjusted.      
Model 1: The results from the M=0.2 model are: SSB2016=3,046; SSBmsy proxy = 40,604; ½ Bmsy proxy=20,302; MSY = 7,049; F2016=.228; Fmsy proxy=F40%msp=.17; B2016/Bmsy proxy=.08; F2016/Fmsy proxy=1.31. Overfishing = yes; overfished = yes. Stock level to Bmsy = Below.     
Model 2: The results from the “M-ramp” model are: SSB2016=3,262; SSBmsy proxy=59,714; 1/2 Bmsy proxy = 29,857; MSY = 10,502; F2016=.237; Fmsy proxy = F40%msp=.18; B2016/Bmsy proxy = .05; F2016/Fmsy proxy = 1.34. Overfishing = yes; overfished = yes. Stock level to Bmsy = Below.    
Both of the models lead to the same conclusion about stock status.  Stock status has not changed since the previous SIS record for GOM cod.

column4: Yellowtail flounder - Georges Bank
column28: An empirical approach is still being used. The lack of a model framework means that historical estimates of fishing mortality rate, biomass, and recruitment cannot be calculated for this stock. Status determination relative to reference points is not possible because reference points cannot be defined. Some survey biomass estimates are provided, but the report does not explicitly state whether any of the estimates, or a function of the estimates, has been accepted and should be used. Although stock status is now considered unknown (for reasons stated above), the TRAC report has several qualitative statements that strongly suggest stock biomass is low and stock productivity is poor.
